JOHANNESBURG - Gauteng Premier David Makhura has admitted that e-tolls have not worked. He's promised to discuss an alternative with President Cyril Ramaphosa. Makhura was delivering the state of the province address earlier. READ: Sanral denies writing off e-toll debt "Honourable Members, we all know that the e-tolls have added to the cost of living for many motorists and public transport users in Gauteng. The new dawn must also bring a solution to the protracted and unresolved problem of e-tolls," says Makhura. Makhura says it is loud and clear for all to see that e-tolls have not worked. "Accordingly, I will engage President Ramaphosa in order to find a new and more equitable funding model to support the continued expansion of Gauteng’s road network and public transport system," he says. eNCA